oc:kn_1893a1d0 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When developing or iterating on any skill" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the Claude A / Claude B iterative development pattern: work with one instance to create the skill, test with a fresh instance on real tasks, observe behavior gaps, return to the authoring instance to refine. Build evaluations BEFORE writing extensive documentation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Evaluation-driven development ensures skills solve real problems rather than documenting imagined ones. The dual-instance pattern catches gaps that the author cannot see from their own perspective." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_4324960f a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating SKILL.md frontmatter and long reference files" ;
    oc:directiveContent "SKILL.md YAML frontmatter requires exactly two fields: 'name' (64 characters max) and 'description' (1024 characters max). For reference files longer than 100 lines, include a table of contents at the top." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These are hard requirements enforced by the skill system. Table of contents ensures Claude can see full scope even with partial reads." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_4d619a3b a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When structuring skill directory layout and SKILL.md content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use progressive disclosure: keep SKILL.md under 500 lines, split content into separate files, and keep all references one level deep from SKILL.md. Claude reads SKILL.md when triggered and additional files only as needed." ;
    oc:hasRationale "One-level-deep references ensure Claude reads complete files. Deep nesting causes partial reads via head commands, resulting in incomplete information" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_532de5d4 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "During skill evaluation and testing" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Test skills with all target models. What works for Opus may need more detail for Haiku. Aim for instructions that work well across all planned models: Haiku needs enough guidance, Sonnet needs clarity, Opus needs to avoid over-explanation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Skills act as additions to models, so effectiveness depends on the underlying model's capabilities and instruction-following tendencies" .

oc:kn_5c4fd83a a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When referencing MCP tools in skill instructions" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use MCP tool references with fully qualified names (ServerName:tool_name) to avoid 'tool not found' errors, especially when multiple MCP servers are available." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without the server prefix, Claude may fail to locate the tool among multiple available MCP servers" ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_62d28ac5 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing utility scripts for skills" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For scripts: handle errors explicitly rather than punting to Claude, document all configuration constants (no magic numbers), and make clear whether Claude should execute the script or read it as reference." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Explicit error handling makes scripts more reliable than generated code. Documented constants allow Claude to understand and adjust values. Clear execution intent prevents misuse." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_9c264a68 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When authoring all skill content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Avoid: time-sensitive information, inconsistent terminology, deeply nested file references (more than one level deep), Windows-style backslash paths, presenting too many options without a clear default, and assuming tools/packages are installed without explicit install instructions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These anti-patterns cause skills to become outdated, confuse Claude with ambiguous references, break on Unix systems, overwhelm with choices, and fail at runtime respectively" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_9c306ca2 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing any SKILL.md content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Skills must be concise — the context window is a shared public good. Challenge every piece of information: does Claude really need this? Can I assume Claude already knows this? Does this paragraph justify its token cost?" ;
    oc:hasRationale "Every token in a loaded SKILL.md competes with conversation history and other context, directly impacting Claude's ability to perform tasks" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_ccb66793 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When naming skills in YAML frontmatter" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use gerund form (verb + -ing) for skill names: 'Processing PDFs', 'Analyzing spreadsheets', 'Managing databases'. Avoid vague names like 'Helper', 'Utils', 'Tools' or overly generic names like 'Documents', 'Data'." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Consistent naming patterns make skills easier to reference, discover, and organize across a skill library" .

oc:kn_cf8f92a5 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding how much specificity to include in skill instructions" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Set appropriate degrees of freedom: high freedom (text instructions) for tasks with multiple valid approaches; medium freedom (pseudocode with parameters) when a preferred pattern exists; low freedom (specific scripts, no parameters) for fragile, error-prone operations requiring exact sequences" ;
    oc:hasRationale "Matching specificity to task fragility prevents both over-constraining flexible tasks and under-specifying critical operations" .

oc:kn_e6cd785d a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing the YAML frontmatter description field" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Descriptions must be specific, include key terms, state both WHAT the skill does and WHEN to use it, and always be written in third person (not 'I can' or 'You can use this')." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The description is injected into the system prompt and used for skill discovery among potentially 100+ skills. Third-person POV prevents discovery problems from inconsistent point-of-view." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

